President Donald Trump issued a proclamation declaring Thursday, November 23, 2017, as a National Day of Thanksgiving. The proclamation highlights the history of Thanksgiving, starting with the Pilgrims who arrived in Plymouth, Massachusetts in 1620 seeking freedom and opportunity. It also mentions how Thanksgiving became a national holiday in 1863, after President Abraham Lincoln proclaimed a day to remember the country's blessings. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of gratitude and charitable spirit, particularly in the wake of recent tragedies such as hurricanes and acts of violence. President Trump encourages Americans to gather with loved ones and offer prayers of thanks for their blessings. The proclamation also acknowledges the brave men and women of the armed forces who may be separated from their loved ones on Thanksgiving.